commentBody:
@Jeb Jones

You've nailed it as far as what bothered me. Even the animal theme answers weren't really answers. I also saw them as gibberish. Never even thought to look for further meaning within. It was also hard to tell which way the unclued answers were supposed to go.

What was worse for me, though, was that the cluing just wasn't very interesting. So it was a lot of effort for not much reward. Still, I admire the constructor's skill at creating this great beast.

@Sam Lyons
I don't know. But there are 143 clues in all, including the - entries.  So that doesn't seem like a terrible percentage.   It seems like there were a lot of short entries, but I assume that has something to do with how to get the theme in there.
It didn't bother me, but I am one who likes that stuff in my puzzles.

@Vaer

I think that my impression may have been formed right off the bat with [What Jason Momoa has, notably]. I know his name from puzzles but I don’t think I’ve seen him in a movie. And I thought, “How on earth would I know something like that?” I’ve since read other posts and yep, it was a gimme for a lot of folks. (I just googled him and yep, those are some steely abs). 

Overall, though, the breadth of clues was excellent. Definitely a solid puzzle.

@Barry Ancona I had a head-slapping moment with CELIA Cruz. I had the ELIA, but I couldn't think of the right letter to start her name. Start it with S? D? C? Then lightning struck. It's CELIA. Of course!

I got CONGREGANT soon after.

Why the head slap? I have some CELIA Cruz CDs (out of thousands). I haven't listened to her rmusic in ages, though.

@Mary

😂😂😂

Yeah, I can imagine it might be just that.

@Asher

That song was the rage in 1999.  Seemed to play everyday on MTV.  

<a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thong_Song" target="_blank">https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thong_Song</a>

@SP

“… the sides were related…”

I think that’s one of the issues I have with this puzzle—the answers bent by the magnets were not related to each other in any way that I found interesting, meaningful or elegant.

@Crab

ETA is the seventh of the 24 letters of the Greek alphabet. 

OBI is a Japanese belt or sash. It’s a cinch, get it?

@Shrike
Agreed. though I cauht on ok, I don't like when entries aren't actually words or abbreviations. E.g., TEEL is not a thing, but was needed to get Abs of steel and eel. 
Still, not a favorite puzzle for me. Tomorrow is another day!

@logical
They weren't attracted to each other, they were attracted to the magnets in the black squares.

Were you maybe playing on an app and didn't see the magnets?

@jaded

Wow, that's a lot. 

Hope things turn for the better for you.

@Dave 

You didn't earn it!

(Now you have to decide for yourself. Which is the point of my reply.)

@Peter and others

I know what Peter means. The school marking of an A in the the US corresponds to an EINS in German schools, but surely the constructor didn't mean that. It would have required knowledge of how German schools grade students' work. Admittedly "German class" made it a bit misleading. 

Still, A book, e.g., is EIN Buch, so I think the clue works.

@Teresa

Peter is correct.  You are correct.  And the clue is correct.  The fact that EIN cannot mean "A" as a grade doesn't mean that it cannot also mean "a" the indefinite article.  (Of course, I'm addressing you, and I'm sure you know, but I'm mentioning it for the general readership.)

Many crossword clues have ambiguities or misdirections, and for one with knowledge of the German grading system, this might have been an unintentional misdirection, but that doesn't mean the constructor goofed.  It just means Peter didn't see the other way the clue works.

@James

Without challenging you in any way, may I ask for an example or two of bad clues?  

If you don't want to answer, that's fine--I'm just interested in comparing how I see a puzzle like this as opposed to others.

@Francis

I can't put my finger on it, exactly, but for me it was a mix of never being on this particular constructor's wavelength and there being a lot of trivia. I wouldn't call it bad clueing, like the OP, but it was thoroughly unenjoyable for me.

(I had some spare time so I broke my own rules about omitting Sundays. I only did the top of the grid. I got the trick almost instantly - ACTION HERO gave it away - but the tedium of dealing with the fill made me abandon the solve)

@Steve L

Large American knowledge base*

The cultural divide is my main obstacle in acing these puzzles.

@Hitch

I'll give you one reason.

Bork.

@Yusuf

Yes! I was not a fan of Bork either.

And as an Asian American, I also found having “egg foo yung” and “noodle bowl” as answers in the same puzzle to be almost disrespectful.

@Michi

I'd really like to understand your point of view as to why inclusion of these two popular restaurant options is offensive to you.  If I were Asian, I'd be glad to be seen, as I am when entries regarding my ethnicity (e.g. REB).

If you don't have a good answer, I'd have to agree with CB and Paul.

@Bruce
芙蓉蛋 (read “fu jung daan” in Cantonese, where the last character, “daan,” means “egg”) is, in fact, a legitimate dish in Chinese cuisine (though I can’t vouch for how authentically it is typically prepared in restaurants in the US).

NOODLE BOWL, on the other hand, strikes me as a bit too generic, but I can’t say it’s technically wrong, either.

@Hitch

The solver should have as much fun, if not more, as the creator (because creating is tough work).   

 Here the creator had a lot more fun? (I'm guessing)

@Paul

If I’m not mistaken, I addressed one person, not 5 billion, and offered how I would feel. I didn’t tell anyone else how to feel, and I asked for an explanation about the original comment. 

I still don’t understand the comment I was replying to. I suppose you do.

@Steve L

You don't think it's presumptuous to say, "If I were..." and then lump together a hugely diverse group of people? How do you know how you would feel if you were Asian?

It's a bad clue for the theme as many have pointed out. Maybe not offensive, but so strained and generic when dealing with different cultures to be "almost disrespectful." At least that's how I interpreted it.

@Paul

Yep, pretty much how I felt as an Asian. It's not really offensive but did rub me the wrong way.

It's like a death by a thousand papercuts: each incident isn't a big deal but it adds up. What makes it worse is having to justify yourself time and time again because people (generally white Americans) don't understand what it's like to be a minority and just think you're are overreacting to a single event.

@jennie

I haven't seen him shirtless since Khal Drogo died either, but for me, those ABS are unforgettable! 

(Sorry @Francis.)

@Tim

That's interesting.  

Would the "Y" simply be missing, or is there more to it than that?

@CB

😀

Irritating as it is when it happens to me, I gotta admit it's a very funny scenario when it's *not* happening to me.

@Petrol 

The Times is, after all, an American newspaper.

"Alpo," like "Oreo," is fill. It's not ideal, but sometimes it's necessary. Puzzle construction is hard.

@Nancy Sculerati MD

I think you’re missing the theme. 1D ABSOF ST is pulled by the magnet to the right at 42A TEEL for the full answer ABS OF STEEL.

If you don’t see the drawings of the four horseshoe magnets, check to be sure Show Overlays is on.

@Eric Hougland

Probably there's a few people who see it as too much of a gimmick. Or something. At least they have the option to shut them off.

I've always enjoyed the overlays. They appeal to my inner three-year-old. And the more color and motion involved, the better.

@Jane Wheelaghan Epps is an actor. Bork is a former candidate for the Supreme Court who was resoundingly rejected by Democratic senators back when such rejections were very rare; his name has come to be synonymous with the past tense of the f word.

Alpo is a dog food, Trix is a breafast cereal, Gregory Hines was a dancer/actor who starred with Barishnikov in "White Nights," Ortega is a brand of taco, the Guinness book of world records has been known over the world for decades...

That's probably more than enough.:-)

@replay

BORK and SNARF only register as a flat line on Google Ngram Viewer if you include SCARF in the search.  SCARF has another meaning, much more mainstream.  Add -ing to your search words, and you'll see that flat line rise a bit.  (Still not that high, though.)

And remember that Ngram only shows printed usage.

@N.E. Body

The animal pairs are not related except in the fact that they are both animals.

The match part (which I missed) was that the pair of answers were related, such as ABS OF STEEL/ACTION STARS, HOUSE OF GOD/CONGREGANT, etc.  The hint was in the title, which I did not pay attention to.

@Jeff Z

Maybe check a dictionary before making pronouncements that are iffy at best:

<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/vegetable" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/vegetable</a>

@retired, with cat
A very good friend hailed from Michiana (South Bend), so I feel your chagrin. 
If you ever want a hoot about state lines in our neck of the woods, read about the Toledo War (fought before Indiana was Indiana).

@Mike
Lots of comments, but yours is the first which offers an alternative which almost makes sense--although "green glass" in my lawn would probably broken Rolling Rock bottles--ouch!

Since (green) grass *is* the lawn, I kept trying to think of something colorful which would be an addition to the lawn, whether wanted (purple thyme) or unwanted (yellow dandelions).

@sotto voce
@Vaer

