I understood why the Blue were Blue, but it was an odd heading.

@James
Well, per the OED, "teel" is a type of Indian sesame seed, or "till" in the Cornish dialect; and "rass" is Jamaican slang for, um . . .; and I once owned a Gant dress shirt--
--but yes, it woiuld have been more elegant if the turns were just the animal names. But that would been almost impossible to pull off, I figure.

@Beth

My assumption is they hit the Comments icon at the very top of the column without scrolling -- or reading -- further. 

Tbh the other day someone commented about needing to go all the way through the column to get to the comments -- and I was confused! 😂

@Beth

Sometimes I find myself reading the full column, then scrolling back up to that itty-bitty icon instead of using the big blue button bar. Compulsive... 😂

And yeah, on the rare occasions I open the crossword on my laptop, the photo and column title are *always* in view in frame, thanks to the resolution my screen is set to. One of the reasons Sam Corbin's posts are such a breath of fresh air! (The photos she chooses are pretty much cryptic in association, in the best way.)

@Ernest
She was a young French saint.

sainte(feminine) in French.

@Brian Sinclair

It's quite consistent.  The animal appears after the bend, because the magnet is attracting it.  It's not attracting any of the other letters, including the one right before it.  If it did, that letter would have to also be turned 90 degrees.  If the first letter of the animal name were in the vertical line, it wouldn't exhibit any attraction.

One might argue that your second nit makes more sense, but it was a lot of work to get the right words to bend and for all of them to have three-letter animals.  It would have been better if they were better matches, but I think that might have been asking the impossible.

@Lena
Ehhh, but A/Ein always inherently means “one”. 
If you say “Ein Mann” there is no question as to how many men there are.

