"In Robert Bork's America, orphaned children will be forced to work in coal mines."

@Jackson

I didn't take it that the he animals were supposed to be attracted to each other. They're attracted to the magnets  and pulling the crossing word along with them because of the power of the magnet. That's my interpretation, but I had a lot of fun with it and seem to be in the minority about that today, which is fine. 

But if an OWL and a GNU want to get together, who made a judge? They're just out there in nature living their best lives!  😉

@Michael

Yeah, some of the theme answers seemed a bit generic to me, too. (GREEN GRASS?) After reading how hard the constructor worked to get this puzzle created, I felt kinda bad for not having more of an "aha!" response. Your expression of "oh, that" resonates... 

Good to see the crossword club is still at it!

@acjones

Would you care to list which clues are wrong so we can look them up for you and explain why they're not wrong? There may be some that are legitimately questionable, but based on the example in your other comment (TINGS), I doubt it. 

If my answer sounds irritable, it's because I don't care for my genuine delight in this puzzle to be called "placating fake enthusiasm" by someone who has never met me or any of the other folks who enjoyed this one.

@HeathieJ

I’m guessing that the OP didn’t understand the puzzle. Several people who panned this puzzle thoroughly did not appear to get the trick. 

(I didn’t find this puzzle as great as some others, but I did see what the trick was, and didn’t mention non-existent mistakes because I didn’t understand the theme.)

@acjones

