When answers appear nonsensical, and then my perception changes and they appear sensical, I like that shift. Like staring at those perceptual puzzles, is it a duck or a rabbit. But YMMV.

@Rob it has 2 meanings and thus 2 origins.

Bork first came into existence when Robert Bork’s nomination for Supreme Court justice was derailed…and so something broken through attacks is “borked”

The second definition is probably an onomatopoeia because the sound “bork” is a little awkward so it sounds like something breaking.  It’s harder to find a history for the second definition.  So it probably was used somewhere after the first bork and caught on.

